{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.4 Optional Consequences and Benefits\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on which approach seems to grow from the story, your GM may assign Consequences of Defeat or Benefits of Victory from Group Simple Contests to the entire group, or to individual members who performed either especially well, or especially poorly. Your GM should default to rewarding or penalizing everyone. Your GM should resort to individualized repercussions or benefits only when a group reward defies dramatic credibility, or when competition within the group is a pivotal dramatic issue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.5 Optional: Boosting Results\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Because they average together the results of multiple participants, group simple contests tend to flatten outcomes, making victories more likely to be marginal or minor than major or complete.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To overcome this flattening effect, you can, at the beginning of a group simple contest, spend one or more Hero Points to purchase a boost. A boost assures a clearer victory, should you prevail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The cost varies by the number of heroes participating:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 Hero Point for 1-3 heroes;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 2 Hero Points for 4-6 heroes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 3 Hero Points for 7-9 heroes.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab and so on\u8230?\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may spend twice as many Hero Points as required to gain a double boost. The points may be spent by any combination of players. They remain spent no matter how the contest resolves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a tie or a victory, the boost increases the collective victory level by one step. A double boost increases it by two steps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 6. Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Hero points are a resource that you must carefully allocate. They allow you to heighten your victories and dull your defeats. They are the price you pay to improve your abilities over time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.1 Gaining Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You get 3 hero points at the beginning of every session. During the session, all Hero Points must be spent, either on improving contest results or character improvement. At the end of the session, unspent points are lost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.2 Improving Your Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may improve any ability by 1 point per session, at a cost of 1 hero point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It costs 1 Hero Point to raise a single breakout ability under the keyword, or 2 points to raise the entire keyword or runic affinity by a point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can add a new ability by spending 1 point; it begins with a rating of 13.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can add a new breakout ability by spending 1 point; it begins with a rating of +1 to the keyword it modifies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.3 Catch-Ups\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A package deal, called a catch-up, applies whenever you acquire a new mastery, up to three abilities or keywords of your choice also increase by 3 points apiece. Only abilities or keywords with values 5 or more points behind your newly adjusted rating in the raised ability qualify for a catch-up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can\u8217't raise abilities under a keyword, nor gain a catch-up when the effective value of a subability reaches a mastery (since it\u8217's the keyword, not the abilities under it, which has a rating).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.4 Directed Improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On occasion your GM may increase one of your abilities, by 1 to 3 points, or give you a new ability, usually rated at 13. These are called directed improvements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Directed improvements are usually rewards for overcoming particularly important or dramatic obstacles. They happen immediately, rather than at session\u8217's end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 7. Relationships\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Abilities may represent your relationship to NPCs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.1 Supporting Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many relationships connect you to NPCs controlled by the GM.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you try to use one of these relationships to solve a problem, your tactic is your relationship ability. You can\u8217't simply go to the supporting character you have a relationship with, stick them with the problem, and expect to see it solved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you succeeds, the supporting character helps you solve the problem. If you fail, they don\u8217't. As with any ability, you must still specify how the NPC goes about overcoming the obstacle. Calls on relationships are almost always simple contests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In crucial situations, it may seem dramatically inappropriate for you to solve a problem indirectly, by working through others. Your GM can expose the supporting character to serious risk. If the character dies or otherwise suffers a change of status that renders him useless to you, you permanently lose the relationship ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before putting supporting characters at serious risk, your GM should make sure the players understand the magnitude of the possible consequences.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When supporting characters undertake significant risk, the supporting character may suffer a consequence of defeat commensurate with the level of the defeat in the contest. Or it may simply be your relationship that is damaged or destroyed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.2 Allies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An ally is a character of roughly the same level of accomplishment as you, often in the same or a similar line of work. For every favor you ask of them, they\u8217'll ask one of you. These reciprocal favors will be roughly equivalent in terms of risk, time commitment, difficulty, and inconvenience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.3 Patrons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Patrons enjoy greater access to resources than you, either through personal ownership (as in a Merchant Prince) or authority (as in the governnor of a province). They may lend you advice or provide them with resources but are too busy and important to personally perform tasks for you. They may hire you to do jobs, or issue orders within a command structure to which you both belong.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a you rolls your Patron relationship, your GM adjusts the difficulty depending on what the you have done for them lately.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.4 Contacts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A contact is a specialist in an occupation, skill, or area of expertise. Contacts provide your information and perform minor favors, but will expect information or small favors from you in return.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can describe a contact as being a particular individual, or as a group of similar individuals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.4.1 Occupational Contacts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any occupational keyword can be treated as a source of contacts. However, using an occupational keyword as a source of contacts will always be a stretch. To more reliably draw on particular contacts associated with a profession, you should take an explicit ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.5 Followers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A follower is a secondary character that travels with you and contributes on a regular basis to your success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two types of followers: sidekicks and retainers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Followers need not be people, or even sentient beings: you can write up a spirit guardian, trusty robot, or companion animal as a follower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.5.1 Sidekick\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sidekick is a secondary character under the your control. Most of the time they stays at your side to render assistance, but they can also go off and perform errands or missions on their own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You should give their sidekick a name. You should, when asked, explain how the sidekick came to be the your follower, and why they continues in that role.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sidekicks start with three abilities, one rated at 17 and the others at 13. Any of these abilities may be a keyword. At least one of them should indicate a personality trait.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the sidekick is nonhuman or a member of an unusual culture, one of its three starting abilities must be its species or culture keyword.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once you have determined the sidekick\u8217's base abilities, they allocate 15 additional points between three of them, spending no more than 10 on any one ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can improve these abilities through the expenditure of Hero Points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may use any of your sidekick\u8217's abilities as your own. The companion can go off and do things without you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.5.2 Replacing Lost Sidekicks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a consequence of defeats in which they participated, sidekicks can be killed or leave your service permanently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Defeat in physical contests can lead to literal death. Metaphorical deaths from non-violent contests indicate a break you. The sidekick may angrily withdraw from your service, but is more likely to sorrowfully retire. You may be able to bring a sidekick back from metaphorical death by overcoming story obstacles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you lose a sidekick, they may create a new one without needing to spend a Hero Point. You must explain how the new sidekick has come to be your new follower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may find it convenient to promote retainers to sidekick status, giving them names and personalities, with a sudden boost in abilities and ratings to match.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.5.3 Retainers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A retainer is a more or less anonymous servant or helper. You may specify a single retainer, or, where appropriate to your character concept, an entire staff of them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Like any other ability, a retainer ability allows you to overcome relevant obstacles by engaging in a contest. To model the contribution of retainers, when you are acting, you can use them to augment your ability. Your GM can rule that consequences of defeat apply to retainers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Retainers generally regard you with all the affection and loyalty due to an employer or master. If you treat them more poorly than is expected for their culture, your GM should increase the difficulty level of attempts to make use of their talents.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you lose retainers for any reason, you can replace them simply by providing a convincing explanation of how you go about it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.6 Relationships as Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Certain relationships with supporting characters act as flaws. They impose obligations on you, prompting your GM to present you with obstacles you have no choice but to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.6.1 Dependents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A dependent is a person, usually a family member or loved one, who requires your aid and protection. Your GM should periodically create storylines in which your dependent is endangered.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Rather than taking a dependent as a flaw, you may find it more fruitful to specify the nature of your relationship as an ability, such as Love for Wife or Love for Son.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.6.2 Adversaries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An adversary is a rival, enemy or other individual who can be relied upon to periodically disrupt your plans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 THe adversary\u8217's goals are probably the opposite of yours, although they could be a bitter rival within the same community, organization, or movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To treat an adversary as an ability, rather than a flaw, describe your emotional response to them. Examples: Hates Leonard Crisp, Fears the Electronaut, Sworn Vengeance Against Heimdall. That way, you still inspire your GM to add the plot elements you desire, but can use your antipathy toward the enemy to augment your target numbers against them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Appendix\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Version Changes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Version 2.2\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Uses of he/she changed to they/their\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Flagged some rules that are not required, as optional to allow those using the SRD to safely omit them if not required.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Clarified that contest results are only reciprocal between PCs. When the contest is against a resistance set by the GM, the results indicate whether the PC gains the prize, and the GM narrates the result for the resistance based on this.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Rephrased the contest results to emphasise: Yes, No, And\u8230?, But\u8230?, This change is designed to dissuade GMs from misunderstanding that the prize is obtained on a marginal victory, one of the most common result types, and instead encourage GMs to allow PCs to fail forward on such a result by introducing downstream complications.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Provided clarity that consequences of defeat and benefit of victory are optional and the GM should focus on using the prize to narrate the outcome of a contest, only applying mechanical benefits if they make sense.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Specific Ability Bonuses are dropped. They were hard for the GM to adjudicate and the same intent is better served by using a stretch on a broad ability when contesting against a PC with a more specific ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A winning group in a Group Simple Contest does not suffer a Consequence of Defeat as a result of a low RP difference victory any more, the GM should narrate consequences from the level of victory, if appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Dropped the negative consequences for the winner in an Extended Contest during the Rising Action. If the winner is a PC the degree of success already suggests consequences in addition to the prize on a marginal victory. So this rule is over-complication.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Made it clear that only a PC should use a parting shot, not the resistance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Switched to addressing you the player, using your GM for the Games Master, and we for the game authors\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Long contests include both extended contest and scored contests. Between 1 and 2 extended contests switched to scored contests, this approach restores both variants, but requires changing the generic name to a long contest.\sa180\par}

